|Derived from Mongolian чулуу ''(chuluu)'' meaning "rock, stone".
|-
|Chuluunbold
|Means "stone-steel" in Mongolian.
|-
|Dzhambul
|Mongolian variant of Dzhamal (Chechen form of Jamal).
|-
|Gan
|Means "steel" or "drought, lack of rain" in Mongolian.
|-
|Gansükh
|Means "steel axe" in Mongolian.
|-
|Gantulga
|Means "steel cooking stand" in Mongolian.
|-
|Ganzorig
|Means "steel courage" in Mongolian.
|-
|Genghis
|From the title ''Genghis'' (or ''Chinggis'') ''Khan'', meaning "universal ruler", which was adopted by the Mongol Empire founder Temujin in the late 12th century.
|-
|Jochi
|From Mongolian зочин ''(zochin)'' meaning "guest".
|-
|Kublai
|From the Mongolian name ''Khubilai'', of unknown meaning. This was the name of a 13th-century grandson of Genghis Khan (being the son of his son Tolui), and the fifth ruler of the Mongol Empire. He is also considered the first ruler of the Chinese Yuan dynasty.
|-
|Mönkhbat
|Variant transcription of Munkhbat.
|-
|Nekhii
|Means "sheepskin" in Mongolian.
|-
|Nergüi
|Means "no name" in Mongolian. This name was traditionally given in order to mislead bad spirits.
|-
|Nugai
|Means "dog" in Mongolian.
|-
|Och
|
|-
|Oktai
|
|-
|Otgonbayar
|Means "youngest joy" in Mongolian.
|-
|Qara
|Means "black" in Azerbaijani.
|-
|Sükh
|Means "axe" in Mongolian, derived from сүх ''(süh)'' "axe".
|-
|Sükhbaatar
|Means "hero of the axe" in Mongolian, derived from сүх ''(süh)'' "axe" and баатар ''(baatar)'' meaning "hero".
|-
|Taimoorkhan
|
|-
|Temujin
|Means "of iron" in Mongolian, derived ultimately from the Turkic word ''temür'' "iron". This was the original name of the Mongolian leader better known by the title Genghis Khan. Born in the 12th century, he managed to unite the tribes of Mongolia and then conquer huge areas of Asia and Eastern Europe.
|-
|Terbish
|Means "not that one" in Mongolian.
|-
|Timicin
|
|-
|Timur
|From the Turkic and Mongol name ''Temür'' meaning "iron". This was the name of several Mongol, Turkic and Yuan leaders. A notable bearer was Timur, also known as ''Tamerlane'' (from Persian ''تیمور لنگ (Timur e Lang)'' meaning "Timur the lame"), a 14th-century Turkic leader who conquered large areas of Western Asia.
|-
|Ulagan
|
|-
|Yul
|Diminutive of Yuliy.
